## Package Managers

- JS dependencies: `npm` (`npm install`, `npm run dev`, `npm test`)
- Python dependencies: `uv` (`uv sync`, `uv add <pkg>`, `uv run <script>`)
- Never mix: do not use `pip` or `yarn`

## Component Architecture

`App.jsx` owns all shared state and handlers. Rendering is delegated to four components:

```
App
├── Summary            props: totalIncome, totalExpenses, balance
├── AddTransaction     props: categories, onSubmit(newTransaction)
│                      owns its own local form state; resets after submit
├── Transactions       props: transactions (pre-filtered), filterType, filterCategory,
│                             categories, onFilterTypeChange, onFilterCategoryChange,
│                             onUpdate(transaction), onDelete(id)
├── ModalActions       props: visible, message, onConfirm, onCancel, children
│   └── <input>        modal-input passed as children from App — Update flow only
└── ModalActions       same shell, no children — Delete flow
```

Component files live in `src/components/`. Do not add state to `Summary` or `Transactions` — they are stateless.

## State Ownership

**`App.jsx` (shared):** `transactions`, `filterType`, `filterCategory`, `pendingDeleteId`, `pendingUpdate`, `updateAmount`

**`AddTransaction.jsx` (local form only):** `description`, `amount`, `type`, `category`

## Data Rules

- `amount` is stored as a **string** on every transaction object
- Always use `parseFloat(t.amount)` for arithmetic — never coerce with `+` or `Number()`
- `totalIncome`, `totalExpenses`, and `balance` are derived on every render in `App.jsx`; never store them in state

## Testing Rules

- Runner: Vitest 4 + jsdom; setup file `src/setupTests.js` imports `@testing-library/jest-dom`
- Always use `userEvent.setup()` — do not call `userEvent` methods directly (legacy API)
- Scope queries with `within(element)` to avoid cross-section matches
  - **Critical gotcha**: `screen.getByText('Income')` is ambiguous — it matches the summary card `<h3>` AND `<option value="income">` elements in both selects. Always use `within(document.querySelector('.summary'))` first
- `beforeEach` renders a fresh `<App>` — no shared state between tests
- Seed data: 8 transactions; `[0]` = Salary (income, $5000), `[1]` = Rent (expense, $1200)
  - Target `deleteButtons[1]` / `updateButtons[1]` when testing expense mutations

## Constraints

- No router, no React context, no external state library
- No data persistence — state resets on page refresh by design
- No backend; all logic is client-side
